default&#xa0;
defaultThis
default defaultcontrasts with Oxfordshire Road Casualty figures (Oxfordshire County Council, 1993),
default defaultwhich report that 68% of cycle accidents occur at junctions. It is well known that cycle
default defaultaccidents are under-represented in accident figures (Mills, 1989)
default but we are addressing here
default defaultthe pattern rather than the absolute number of accidents. National figures (Department of
default defaultTransport, 1992) also suggest that at least two-thirds of cycle accidents occur at junctions.
default  defaultWe suggest that these official figures almo
defaultst certainly relate more to the classification of
default defaultaccidents than to the nature of what is happening on the road. The police STATS 19 records
default defaultclassify an accident as occurring at a junction irrespective of whether the manoeuvre of either
default 
defaultvehicle concerned i
defaultnvolved the junction or merely happened in the vicinity of a junction.
default  default&#xa0;defaultWith this query in mind, we asked the Department of Transport’s Directorate of Statistics todefault defaultanalyse national pedal cycle casualty figures by cross-tabulating cyclists’ actions with defaultthedefault defaultactions of those involved in accidents with them. Of the 25,421 cycle accidents in 1991,default default13.8% involved cyclists turning right or left and a further 28.9% involved other vehiclesdefault defaultturning right or left. This suggests that only 42.7% of cycle accidents idefaultnvolve turns atdefault defaultjunctions, which is considerably closer to estimates in the diary data than the usual two-thirdsdefault defaultfigure quoteddefault.
default defaultThe major manoeuvre of other vehicles which cyclists reported in the current study wasdefault defaultbeing overtaken too closely in a straightdefault-ahead situationdefault. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is notable that an Australian
default defaultstudy, examining the characteristics of fatal as compared to total cycle accidents, finds that
default defaultfatal accidents are less likely to be at intersections than are non-fatal accidents (Hoque,
default default1990). 
default 
defaultOur data
default also accord with the British Medical Association’s (1992) review, which
default defaultcomments that most adult cyclist fatalities are caused by a vehicle approaching from
default defaultbehind 
default—which presumably includes errors in overtaking. The Highway Code (Department of
default defaultEnvironmen
defaultt, Transport and the Regions, 1999b) inf
defaultorms motorists that they should 
default‘give
default default[cyclists] at least as much room as you would give a car’ (p. 18), although the accompanying
default defaultillustration suggests a less generous margin of overtaking than did the illustration 
defaultin the 1993
default defaultedition (Department 
defaultof Transport, 1993). The cyclists in our study clearly felt that they were
default defaultnot given the margin they required by passing motor vehicles, particularly buses. It is possible
default defaultthat buses overtake cycles with no narrower a margin
default than cars do, but threaten cyclists more
default defaulton account of their greater size. A film record would be needed to establish whether cyclists’
default defaultperceptions of risk relate more to the size, speed or position of the passing vehicle.
